*Removed from the susceptible population through death, destruction and/or slaughter

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: Unknown or inconclusive, Vectors

Epidemiological comments: Tsetse flies are not present in the country; it is thought that the transmission occurred through other hematophagous flies (horsefly or _Stomoxys_ sp.), which explains the limited spreading of the disease and epidemiological impact. The investigation carried out to identify the origin of those outbreaks revealed the existence of unofficial registers related to the possible detection of the agent in the provinces of Chaco and Formosa in the past. The presence of the agent in these areas could have been hidden by the existence of endemic diseases with indistinguishable symptomatology, such as babesiosis and anaplasmosis. We will attempt to clarify this point in order to integrate this information within next periodic reports.

Control measures
Measures applied: movement control inside the country; traceability; quarantine; control of vectors; vaccination permitted ( if a vaccine exists); treatment of affected animals (Dimenazeno)

Measures to be applied: no other measures

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type / Species / Test / Test date / Result
Investigation and transfer center of Formosa (Local laboratory) / Cattle / polymerase chain reaction (PCR) / 22 May 2017 / Positive

Future reporting
The event is continuing. Weekly follow-up reports will be submitted.

